    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense, but when i'm drawing the actual tree, it feels like there's no clear way to know which one is right just by looking at the words. if i'm mapping out the branching structure, how do i determine if the PP is a daughter of the NP or a daughter of the VP? is there a specific formal logic or hierarchy used in syntax to resolve that attachment?",
      "source": "evaluator",
      "targeted_response_start": "",
      "beast_baseline": "that makes sense, but when i'm drawing the actual tree, it feels like there's no clear way to know which one is right just by looking at the words. if i'm mapping out the branching structure, how do i determine if the PP is a daughter of the NP or a daughter of the VP? is there a specific formal logic or hierarchy used in syntax to resolve that attachment?",
      "beast_suffix": "",
      "targeted_response_start_logprob": 0.0
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "In formal syntax, resolving this ambiguity often requires looking at semantic constraints or established attachment preferences, like subcategorization frames or thematic roles. If the PP acts as an instrument for the verb (e.g., *saw*), it typically attaches to the VP; if it acts as a modifier describing the head noun (e.g., *man*), it attaches to the NP. There isn't a single, simple formal rule, but rather a hierarchy of preference based on the type of relation the PP expresses (e.g., instrumental vs. descriptive).",
      "source": "target",
